'''Distraction osteogenesis''', also called '''callus distraction''',<ref name="DeBastiani87">{{harvnb|De Bastiani|1987}}</ref> '''callotasis'''<ref name="DeBastiani87" /> and '''osteodistraction'''<ref name="Tavakoli98">{{harvnb|Tavakoli|1998}}</ref> is a [[Surgery|surgical]] process used to reconstruct [[Skeleton|skeletal]] [[Deformity|deformities]] and lengthen the [[long bone]]s of the body.  A [[corticotomy]] is used to [[bone fracture|fracture]] the [[bone]] into two segments, and the two bone ends of the bone are gradually moved apart during the distraction phase, allowing [[Bone healing|new bone]] to form in the gap.<ref name="DeBastiani87" /><ref name="Paley97Comparison">{{harvnb|Paley|1997}}</ref><ref name="Aquerreta94">{{harvnb|Aquerreta|1994}}</ref> When the desired or possible length is reached, a ''consolidation phase'' follows in which the bone is allowed to keep healing.  Distraction osteogenesis has the benefit of simultaneously increasing bone length and the volume of surrounding [[soft tissue]]s. 

Although distraction technology has been used mainly in the field of [[Orthopedic surgery|orthopedic]]s, early results in rats<ref name="Mehrara99">{{harvnb|Mehrara|1999}}</ref> and humans<ref name="Chin96Maxillofacial">{{cite journal
 | author = Chin, M.
 | coauthors = Toth, B.A.
 | year = 1996
 | title = Distraction osteogenesis in maxillofacial surgery using internal devices: review of five cases.
 | journal = J Oral Maxillofac Surg
 | volume = 54
 | issue = 1
 | pages = 45–53
 | accessdate = 2008-07-10
 | doi = 10.1016/S0278-2391(96)90303-1
 | pmid = 8530999
}}</ref> indicated that the process can be applied to correct deformities of the [[jaw]]. These techniques are now utilised extensively by [[Oral and maxillofacial surgery|maxillofacial surgeons]] for the correction of micrognathia, midface, and fronto-orbital hypoplasia in patients with [[craniofacial]] deformities.

==History==
In 1905, [[Alessandro Codivilla]] introduced surgical practices for lengthening of the lower limbs.<ref name="Codivilla1905">{{cite journal | last = Codivilla | first = Alessandro | year = 1905 | title = On the means of lengthening in the lower limbs, the muscles, and tissues which are shortened through deformity. | journal = American Journal of Orthopedics Surgery" | volume = 2 | pages = 353 }}</ref> Early techniques had a high number of [[Complication (medicine)|complications]], particularly during [[Bone healing|healing]], and often resulted in a failure to achieve the goal of the surgery.<ref name="Mosca86">{{cite journal | last = Mosca | first = V. | coauthors = Moseley, C.F. | year = 1986 | title = Complications of Wagner leg lengthening and their avoidance | journal = Orthop. Trans. | volume = 10 | pages = 462 }}</ref><ref name="Baumgart97" />

In 1934 the New York Hospital For Joint Disease worked on an early method developed by Ilizarov.  The major item that the US team of surgeons developed was the metal frame the leg was placed in to hold it perfectly in place until the cut made in the bone was healed over.<ref>[http://books.google.com/books?id=HCgDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA27&dq=Popular+Science+1931+plane&hl=en&ei=dvsKTffpK8ShnAfqofGVDg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=4&ved=0CDEQ6AEwAzgK#v=onepage&q&f=true "Surgeon Stretches Crippled Legs", September 1934, Popular Science]</ref>

The breakthrough came with a technique introduced by [[Russia]]n orthopedic surgeon [[Gavriil Ilizarov]].<ref name="Baumgart97" />  Ilizarov developed a procedure based on the biology of the bone and on the ability of the surrounding [[soft-tissues]] to regenerate under [[Tension (physics)|tension]]; the technique involved an external fixator, the [[Ilizarov apparatus]], structured as a modular ring.<ref name="Baumgart97" />  Although the types of complications remained the same ([[infection]], the most common complication occurring particularly along the pin tracks, [[pain]], [[nerve]] and [[soft tissue]] irritation<ref name="Baumgart97" />) the Ilizarov technique reduced the frequency and severity of the complications.<ref name="Paley90IlizarovComplications" />  The Ilizarov technique made the surgery safer,<ref name="Palye88techniques">{{cite journal | last = Paley | first = Dror | year = 1988 | title = Current techniques of limb lengthening | journal = Journal of Pediatric Orthopaedics | volume = 8 | issue = 1 | pages = 73–92 | pmid = 3275690 | doi = 10.1097/01241398-198801000-00018 }}</ref> and allowed the goal of lengthening the limb to be achieved.

==Difficulties arising during distraction osteogenesis==
Difficulties that may arise during distraction osteogenesis are commonly classified in medical scientific literature according to the standard introduced by professor [[Dror Paley]] in a 1990 article.<ref name="Paley90IlizarovComplications" /> Paley distinguished among problems (defined as "''a difficulty that arises during the distraction or fixation period that is fully resolved by the end of the treatment period by non operative means''"), obstacles, and complications.

==Techniques==
===Using exclusively an external fixator===
The most common is the Ilizarov surgery with the Ilizarov external fixator. Other external fixators are Wagner,<ref name="WagnerLongTerm">{{cite journal |doi=10.1097/00004694-200205000-00021 |author=Zarzycki D, Tesiorowski M, Zarzycka M, Kacki W, Jasiewicz B |title=Long-term results of lower limb lengthening by the Wagner method |journal=J Pediatr Orthop |volume=22 |issue=3 |pages=371–4 |year=2002 |pmid=11961458 |url=http://meta.wkhealth.com/pt/pt-core/template-journal/lwwgateway/media/landingpage.htm?issn=0271-6798&volume=22&issue=3&spage=371}}</ref> Orthofix and Judet. Dr. Helong Bai (8th Hospital in Chongqing, China) developed the technique "Micro-wound" with a different apparatus.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.shortsupport.org/Health/Leg-Lengthening/new_devel.html |title=Short Persons Support: Health : Cosmetic Leg Lengthening : New Procedures }}</ref>

====Ilizarov surgery====
{{main|Ilizarov apparatus}}
<!-- Image with unknown copyright status removed: [[Image:Ilizarov_external_fixator.jpg|thumb|right|320px|Ilizarov external fixator]] -->
[[Image:Ilizarov.jpg|right]]
Ilizarov [[surgery]], developed by [[Gavriil Ilizarov]], a [[Russians|Russian]] orthopedic [[surgery|surgeon]], in 1951, is the oldest and most common method of distraction osteogenesis. It often brings complications,<ref name="Paley90IlizarovComplications">{{cite journal
 | last = Paley
 | first = Dror 
 | year = 1990
 | month = January 
 | title = Problems, Obstacles, and Complications of Limb Lengthening by the Ilizarov Technique
 | journal = Clinical Orthopaedics & Related Research
 | volume = 250
 | pages = 81–104
 | url = http://www.corronline.com/pt/re/corr/abstract.00003086-199001000-00011.htm
 }}</ref> while some new methods have a much lower rate of complications. 

The process involves the following:
* Shattered bones and [[Blood vessel|devascularised]] ones are removed from the patient, leaving a gap;
* The healthy part of the upper bone is broken into two segments with an external [[saw]];
* The leg is then fitted with the Ilizarov frame that pierces through the [[skin]], [[muscle]]s, and bone;
* [[Screw]]s attached to the middle bone are turned 1 millimetre (mm) per day, so that new [[Osseous tissue|bone tissues]] that are formed in the growth zone are gradually pulled apart to increase the gap (One millimetre has been found to be the [[Optimization (mathematics)|optimal]] bone distraction rate. Lengthening too fast overstretches the soft tissues, resulting not only in pain, but also in the inability of the bone to fill up the gap; too slow, and the bone hardens before the full lengthening process is complete.);
* After the gap is closed, the patient continues to wear the frame until the new bone solidifies; the waiting period before the frame can be removed is usually one month per centimetre of lengthened bone.

Ilizarov surgery is extremely painful, uncomfortable, [[infection]]-prone, and often causes unsightly [[scar]]s ''{{Citation needed|date=November 2011}}''. Frames used to be made of [[stainless steel]] rings weighing up to 7 kilogram (kg), but newer models are made of [[Carbon fiber reinforced plastic]], which though lighter, are equally cumbersome.

Derivative devices provide physicians better control over the bone axis and angle during elongation, such as the [[Taylor Spatial Frame]] (TSF) which is computer assisted. The downside of these developments are their relative complexity and resulting longer learning curve.

For decades, the Ilizarov procedure was the best chance for shattered bones to be restored, and crooked ones straightened. Breakthroughs in distraction osteogenesis in the 1990s, however, have resulted in less painful (albeit more expensive) alternatives, such as unilateral rails.

