The most important aspects for the success of bone distraction are an intact medullary blood supply, preservation of soft-tissue envelope, primarily the [[periosteum]] (which helps preserve the blood supply) and secondarly [[bone marrow]] and the stability of the fixator.<ref name="Guichet03">{{cite journal | last = Guichet | first = Jean-Marc | coauthors = Barbara Deromedis, Leo T. Donnan, Giovanni Peretti, Pierre Lascombes and Flavio Bado | date=1 May 2003| title = Gradual Femoral Lengthening with the Albizzia Intramedullary Nail | journal = [[The Journal of Bone and Joint Surgery]] (American) | volume = 85-A | issue=5 | pages = 838–848 | url = http://www.ejbjs.org/cgi/content/abstract/85/5/838 | pmid = 12728034 | format = abstract }}</ref><ref name="Delloye90">{{cite journal | last = Delloye | first = C | coauthors = Delefortrie G, Coutelier L, Vincent A. | month=January | year = 1990 | title = Bone regenerate formation in cortical bone during distraction lengthening. An experimental study | journal = Clinical Orthopaedics & Related Research | volume = 250 | pages = 34–42 | url = http://www.corronline.com/pt/re/corr/abstract.00003086-199001000-00005.htm | format = abstract}}</ref><ref name="Aldegheri93">{{cite journal | last = Aldegheri | first = R | year = 1993 | title = Callotasis | journal = Journal of Pediatric Orthopaedics}}</ref><ref name="Guichet98">{{cite journal | last = Guichet | first = Jean-Marc | coauthors = Braillon P, Bodenreider O, Lascombes P | month=October| year = 1998 | title = Periosteum and bone marrow in bone lengthening: a DEXA quantitative evaluation in rabbits | journal = [[Acta Orthopaedica Scandinavica]] | volume = 69 | issue = 5 |pages = 527–31 | pmid = 9855238 | doi = 10.3109/17453679808997792}}</ref><ref name="Guichet99">{{cite book |last=Guichet |first=Jean-Marc |title=Bone formation during limb lengthening. Animal experimentation with and without preservation of the bone marrow and/or periosteum |year=1999 |month=September |publisher=New York University |location=New York }}</ref>

===Distraction rate===
The distraction rate must be gradual, as a rapid rate of distraction will result in a fibrous union in which the bone pieces are joined by [[Fibrous connective tissue|fibrous]], rather than [[osseous tissue]].<ref name="RatAcuteLengthening">{{cite journal |doi=10.1097/00006534-200102000-00021 |author=Warren SM, Mehrara BJ, Steinbrech DS, ''et al.'' |title=Rat mandibular distraction osteogenesis: part III. Gradual distraction versus acute lengthening |journal=Plast. Reconstr. Surg. |volume=107 |issue=2 |pages=441–53 |year=2001 |month=February |pmid=11214060 |url=http://meta.wkhealth.com/pt/pt-core/template-journal/lwwgateway/media/landingpage.htm?issn=0032-1052&volume=107&issue=2&spage=441}}</ref><ref name="biologyonline">''[http://www.biology-online.org/dictionary/Fibrous_union fibrous union]'' on biologyonline</ref>

Too slow of a distraction rate would result in early bone consolidation. A common distraction rate for lower limbs is 1 millimeter per day.<ref name="DistractionRate">{{cite journal  |author= ALDEGHERI, R. |title=Distraction Osteogenesis for Lengthening of the Tibia in Patients Who Have Limb-Length Discrepancy or Short Stature |journal=The Journal of Bone and Joint Surgery |volume=81 |issue=5 |pages=624–634 |year=1999 |month=May |pmid=10360691 |url=http://jbjs.org/article.aspx?Volume=81&page=624}}</ref>

===Complications===
In a 2004 study<ref name="deBilly2001Complications">{{cite journal |author=de Billy B, Langlais J, Pouliquen JC, Guichet JM, Damsin JP |title=Complications in lengthening of the femur using different methods |journal=Http://proceedings.jbjs.org.uk/cgi/content/abstract/87-B/SUPP_I/70-c |volume=87-B |issue=Supp I |pages=70 |url=http://proceedings.jbjs.org.uk/cgi/content/abstract/87-B/SUPP_I/70-c}}</ref> lengthening with an exclusively intramedullary nail (Albizzia) had a "significant lower rate" of complications respect to exclusively external methods (Judet, Orthofix, Ilizarov and Wagner fixators).

==Possible uses of distraction osteogenesis==
Although distraction osteogenesis is most often used in the treatment of post-[[Physical trauma|traumatic]] injuries, it is increasingly used to correct limb discrepancies caused by [[Congenital disorder|congenital conditions]] and old injuries. A list of the possible uses of distraction osteogenesis are as follows:

* Congenital deformities (birth defects):
** Congenital short [[femur]].
** [[Fibular hemimelia]] (absence of the [[fibula]], which is one of the two bones between the knee and the ankle).
** [[Hemihypertrophy]] (a rare genetic condition in which growth is greater on one side of the body. This can be complete (everything from the bone to the skin on one entire half of the body) or partial (just one leg or arm).
** [[Ollier's disease]].
* Developmental deformities
** [[Neurofibromatosis]] (a rare condition which causes overgrowth in one leg); and
** Bow legs, resulting from [[rickets]] or secondary [[arthritis]].
* Post-traumatic injuries
** [[Growth plate]]s fractures;
** Malunion or non-union (when bones do not completely join, or join in a faulty position after a fracture);
** Shortening and deformity; and
** Bone defects.
* Infections and [[disease]]s
** [[Osteomyelitis]] (a bone infection, usually caused by [[bacteria]]);
** [[Septic arthritis]] (infections or bacterial arthritis); and
** [[Poliomyelitis]] (a [[Virus|viral]] disease which may result in the atrophy of muscles, causing permanent deformity).
* After [[tumor]]s
* [[Short stature]]
** [[Achondroplasia]] (a form of [[dwarfism]] where arms and legs are very short, but [[torso]] is more normal in size); and
** [[Constitutional short stature]].

===Cosmetic lengthening of limbs===
Generally, doctors tend to discourage{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}} [[beauty|cosmetic]] lengthening for people who want to add a couple of inches to their frames because such people are:
* breaking perfectly functional limbs;
* confining themselves unnecessarily to [[crutch]]es or a [[wheelchair]] for over a year;
* voluntarily subjecting themselves to pain and discomfort;
* exposing themselves to unnecessary  risk of infections, of damaged nerves and blood vessels, and fat [[embolism]] that can result in death; and
* incurring unnecessary expenses as the procedure is relatively expensive.{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}}

People insistent on doing the procedure, however, are required by some doctors{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}} to undergo a thorough [[body image]] [[Psychological assessment|assessment]] by a [[psychologist]] to help determine how far the person's quality of life has been affected by his perceived lack of height, and if doing the surgery will make a marked difference.

==In popular culture==

The protagonist of the movie ''[[Gattaca]]'' undergoes a limb lengthening procedure, along with other extreme methods, in order to impersonate another person and thus avoid genetic discrimination.

In [[Ian Fleming]]'s James Bond novel ''[[Dr. No (novel)|Dr. No]]'', Dr. No alludes to using leg-lengthing to increase his height to roughly 7 feet tall as part of a larger scheme to mask his identity.

